In RSpec, allow itself does NOT have many methods.

This part:

allow(object).to receive(:method)

allow returns a message expectation object, and that object supports many chaining methods.

So what you’re really asking is:

“What methods can I chain after allow(...).to receive(...)?”

Let’s categorize them properly.

🧠 1️⃣ Basic Stubbing
Basic allow
allow(object).to receive(:method)

Just allows the method. Returns nil by default.

and_return
allow(object).to receive(:method).and_return(value)

Multiple returns:

allow(object).to receive(:method).and_return(1, 2, 3)

Each call returns next value.

🧠 2️⃣ and_raise
allow(object).to receive(:method).and_raise(StandardError)

Raise specific error:

allow(object).to receive(:method)
  .and_raise(ArgumentError, "invalid")
🧠 3️⃣ and_throw
allow(object).to receive(:method).and_throw(:done)
🧠 4️⃣ and_call_original

Very important.

allow(object).to receive(:method).and_call_original

Stubs method

But still calls real implementation

Used in partial doubles.

🧠 5️⃣ and_wrap_original

Wrap original method:

allow(object).to receive(:method).and_wrap_original do |original, *args|
  result = original.call(*args)
  result.upcase
end

Useful for modifying behavior.

🧠 6️⃣ with (Argument Matching)
allow(object).to receive(:method).with(1, 2).and_return(3)

Different returns for different args:

allow(object).to receive(:method).with(1).and_return("one")
allow(object).to receive(:method).with(2).and_return("two")
🧠 7️⃣ Argument Matchers

Used with with.

with(anything)
with(any_args)
with(no_args)
with(kind_of(String))
with(instance_of(User))
with(hash_including(name: "Shubham"))
with(array_including(1,2))
🧠 8️⃣ allow_any_instance_of (Special Case)
allow_any_instance_of(User)
  .to receive(:admin?)
  .and_return(true)

Dangerous (we discussed earlier).

🧠 9️⃣ stub_const

Not directly chained to allow, but related to stubbing.

stub_const("PaymentGateway", fake_class)

Used to replace constants.

🧠 🔟 receive_messages

Stub multiple methods at once:

allow(object).to receive_messages(
  name: "Shubham",
  age: 25
)
🧠 1️⃣1️⃣ receive_message_chain (⚠️ Discouraged)
allow(object)
  .to receive_message_chain(:a, :b, :c)
  .and_return(1)

Avoid — considered code smell.

🧠 1️⃣2️⃣ once / twice / exactly (Less common with allow)

Mostly used with expect, but technically possible:

allow(object).to receive(:method).once

However, frequency constraints are normally for expect.

🧠 1️⃣3️⃣ ordered

Mostly used with expect, but available.

allow(object).to receive(:method).ordered
